`,s.jsxs(e.p,{children:['In supervised learning, every training example comes with a label. A spam filter knows which emails are spam; a tumour detector knows which scans are malignant. The label guides the model. But in the real world, labels are expensive. Annotating one million customer transactions as "fraudulent" or "legitimate" requires human reviewers, legal review, and days of labour. What if we could discover structure in the data ',s.jsx(e.em,{children:"without any labels at all"}),"?"]}),`
`,s.jsxs(e.p,{children:["This is the promise of ",s.jsx(e.strong,{children:"unsupervised learning"}),", and clustering is its most widely used technique. Instead of predicting a target, we ask a simpler question: which data points are similar to one another? Group similar things together and keep dissimilar things apart — and structure often emerges that no human thought to label in advance."]}),`
